          "body": "Jeremiah 20 opens with a swift, brutal scene. Pashhur, the chief officer of the temple, hears Jeremiah prophesying and immediately has him beaten and locked in the stocks at the most public gate of the temple complex (20:1-2). The act is significant beyond its cruelty. Pashhur represents the institutionalized religious establishment that had every reason to suppress Jeremiah's message — the temple was the center of national identity, its destruction was unthinkable, and Jeremiah had been announcing exactly that for years (chapters 7, 19). Pashhur's response is the response of every institution to the prophet who threatens its survival: suppress the messenger. But the arrest itself becomes the occasion for a more devastating word. Upon release, Jeremiah does not recant, comfort, or soften. He renames Pashhur — 'Magor-missabib,' terror on every side — and announces that the very man who tried to silence the message will personally live to see everything the message said come true (20:3-6). The priest who protected the temple will be buried in Babylon. The chapter opens by demonstrating that no earthly authority can extinguish the prophetic word."
